.Dd Mar 7, 2026
.Dt mclogd.cfg 5
.Os
.Sh NAME
.Nm mclogd.cfg
.Nd mclogd configuration file.
.Sh SYNOPSIS
.Nm
.Sh DESCRIPTION
.Nm
is the configuration file for
.Xr mclogd 8 .
Its default location is \fI@prefix@/etc/mclogd.cfg\fR and an example can be
found in \fI@prefix@/etc/mclogd.cfg.example\fR

.Sh FILE FORMAT
.Nm
contains multiple stanzas.  Stanzas are opened with a name and \fB{\fR and
closed with \fB};\fR.  There are five valid top-level stanza names:
\fIservice\fR, \fIloopback\fR, \fIfilters\fR, \fImulticast\fR and
\fIfiles\fR.
.Pp
Comments start with \fB#\fR and continue to the end of the line.  Empty
lines are ignored.
.Ss "service" \fRstanza
The service stanza contains settings for authentication.
.Bl -tag -width "   " indent
.It \fB keyDirectory = \fIpath\fR;
The credence key directory.
.El
.Pp
An example service stanza is shown below.
.Pp
.Bd -literal
    service {
        keyDirectory = "/usr/local/etc/mclogd";
    };
.Ed
.Ss loopback\fR stanza
The loopback stanza is used to enable listening on the IPv4 loopback and/or
IPV6 loopback, and on which UDP port to listen.
.Bl -tag -width "   " indent
.It \fB listenV4 = \fIboolean\fR;
Should
.Xr mclogd 8
listen on the IPv4 loopback address?  The default is \fItrue\fR.
.It \fB listenV6 = \fIboolean\fR;
Should
.Xr mclogd 8
listen on the IPv6 loopback address?  The default is \fIfalse\fR.
.It \fB port = \fIport\fR;
The UDP port on which
.Xr mclogd 8
should listen for local messages (via the loopback address).  The default
value is 3737.
.El
.Pp
An example loopback stanza is below.
.Pp
.Bd -literal
    loopback {
       listenV4 = true;    # listen on 127.0.0.1?
       listenV6 = false;   # listen on ::1?
       port = 3737;        # port on which to listen (default 3737)
    };
.Ed
.Ss filters stanza
.Pp
The filters stanza may be used to define named filter expressions or
filter expression fragments which can later be referenced by name
(with a preceding dollar sign $).  This makes the construction of longer
filter expressions a bit more convenient.  Note that a name must be fully
defined set before referenced; referencing a name before its value is
set is undefined.
.Pp
.Bl -tag -width "   " indent
.It \fB <name> = \(dq\fI<filter expression>\fR\(dq;
Creates a filter expression named \fB<name>\fR with value
\fI<filter expression>\fR.
.El
.Pp
An example filters stanza is shown below.  Note how we refer to previously
defined names \fIapps\fR and \fImyhosts\fR when defining \fImyapps\fR
and \fIdaemons\fR and \fImyhosts\fR when defining \fImydaemons\fR.
.Pp
.Bd -literal
    filters {
        apps = "ident = /mc(block|curtain|rover|tally)|qmcrover/";
        daemons = "ident = /mc(block|curtain|log|rover|tally|weather)d/";
        myhosts = "host = /.+\.(mcplex\.net|rfdm\.com)/";
        myapps = "($apps) && ($myhosts)";
        mydaemons = "($daemons) && ($myhosts)";
    };
.Ed
See the
.Sx FILTER EXPRESSIONS
section for filter grammar.
.Ss multicast stanza
.Pp
The multicast stanza is used to set the interface that
.Xr mclogd 8
will use for multicast as well as the multicast group and UDP port that
will be used.
.Pp
For IPv4 multicast, two settings are needed: \fIintfAddr\fR and
\fIgroupAddr\fR.
.Pp
.Bl -tag -width "   " indent
.It \fB intfAddr = \(dq\fI<IPv4 address>\fR\(dq;
The IPv4 address of the interface on which
.Xr mclogd 8
should send and receive IPv4 multicast messages.
.It \fB groupAddr = \(dq\fI<IPv4 multicast address>\fR\(dq;
The IPv4 multicast group address to which we will send log messages we
received via the loopback and from which we will receive log messages
from other instances of
.Xr mclogd 8 via multicast.
The default value is 239.108.111.103
.El
.Pp
For IPv6 multicast, three settings are needed: \fIintfAddr6\fR,
\fIgroupAddr6\fR and \fIintfName\fR.
.Pp
.Bl -tag -width "   " indent
.It \fB intfAddr6 = \(dq\fI<IPv6 address>\fR\(dq;
The IPv6 address of the interface on which
.Xr mclogd 8
should send and receive IPv6 multicast messages.
.It \fB groupAddr6 = \(dq\fI<IPv6 multicast address>\fR\(dq;
The IPv4 multicast group address to which we will send log messages we
received via the loopback and from which we will receive log messages
from other instances of
.Xr mclogd 8 via multicast.  The default is ff02::006d:636c:6f67
.It \fB intfName = \(dq\fI<interface name>\fR\(dq;
The name of the interface on which we will send and receive IPv6
multicast messages.  This interface must have the address specified
as \fIintfAddr6\fR.
.El
.Pp
Both IPv4 and IPv6 multicast utilize the same UDP port number and
output filter expression.
.Pp
.Bl -tag -width "   " indent
.It \fB port = \fI<port number>\fR;
The port number to use for sending and receiving multicast messages.
the default is 3737.
.It \fB outFilter = \(dq\fI<filter expression>\fR\(dq;
A filter expression to select the log messages which
.Xr mclogd 8
will send via multicast.  The default value is empty, which will cause
.Xr mclogd 8
to send all local messages (received on the loopback) to the IPv4 and
IPv6 multicast groups.  See the
.Sx FILTER EXPRESSIONS
section for filter grammar.
.El
.Pp
An example multicast stanza is shown below.
.Bd -literal
   multicast {
      #------------------------------------------------------------------
      #  For IPv4, we need the interface address and the multicast group
      #  address.
      #------------------------------------------------------------------
      intfAddr = "192.168.168.42";
      groupAddr = "239.108.111.103";
      #------------------------------------------------------------------
      #  For IPv6, we need the interface address, the multicast group
      #  address and the interface name.
      #------------------------------------------------------------------
      intfAddr6 = "fd60:3019:f4a:6aaf::39";
      groupAddr6 = "ff02::006d:636c:6f67";
      intfName = "en0";
      #------------------------------------------------------------------
      #  We use the same destination port for IPv4 and IPv6.
      #------------------------------------------------------------------
      port = 3737;

      outFilter = "$mydaemons";
   };
.Ed
.Ss files stanza
The files stanza has two components: \fIlogDirectory\fR and \fIlogs\fR.
.Pp
.Bl -tag -width "   " indent
.It \fB logDirectory = \(dq\fI<path to directory>\fR\(dq;
Specify the top level directory for log files.  The default value
is \fI/usr/local/var/mclog\fR.
.It \fB logs { \fI<log entry>\fR [, \fIlog entry> ...] };
Specify a list of log entries.  Log entries are described below.
.El
.Pp
Each log entry in \fIlogs\fR is started with a \fB{\fR and ended with
a \fB}\fR, with a comma \fB,\fR between entries.  Each log entry has
the following settings.
.Pp
.Bl -tag -width "   " indent
.It \fB filter = \(dq\fI<filter expression>\fR\(dq;
Only messages which match the given \fI<filter expression>\fR will be saved
to the log.
.It \fB path = \(dq\fI<path>\fR\(dq;
The path to the log.  If this is a relative path, it will be rooted at
\fIlogDirectory\fR.  In addition, three substitutions based on message
content may be contained in \fI<path>\fR:
.Pp
.Bl -compact -tag -width "   " indent
.It \fB%H\fR
Replaced by the hostname of the message origin.
.It \fB%I\fR
Replaced by the message's identity (program name).
.It \fB%F\fR
Replaced by the message's facility ('user', 'daemon', 'local0', et. al.).
.El
.Pp
If no 'path' is specified, \(dq%H/%I\(dq will be used.
.It \fB period = \fI<period>\fR;
The period before the log will be rolled to a log archive.  Valid values
for \fI<period>\fR:
.Pp
.Bl -compact -tag -width "   " indent
.It \fB5m\fR
5 minutes
.It \fB15m\fR
15 minutes
.It \fB30m\fR
30 minutes
.It \fB1h\fR
1 hour
.It \fB2h\fR
2 hours
.It \fB4h\fR
4 hours
.It \fB6h\fR
6 hours
.It \fB8h\fR
8 hours
.It \fB12h\fR
12 hours
.It \fB1d\fR
1 day
.It \fB7d\fR
7 days
.El
.Pp
The default period is \fI1d\fR.
.Pp
Note that
.Xr mclogd 8
will roll over a log when it exceeds the \fIsize\fR or the \fIperiod\fR
has transpired, whichever comes first.
.It \fB size = \fI<size>\fR;
The allowed size of the log (in bytes) before it will rolled over to a
log archive.  Note that
.Xr mclogd 8
will roll over a log when it exceeds the \fIsize\fR or the \fIperiod\fR
has transpired, whichever comes first.
,Pp
The default value is 0, which disables size-based log rollover.    
.It \fB keep = \fI<keep>\fR;
The number of log archives to keep.  The default is 7.
.It \fB compress = \fI<compression>\fR;
The type of compression to use for log archives, either \(dqbzip2\(dq
    or \(dqgzip\(dq.  The default is \(dqbzip2\(dq.
.It \fB perms = \fI<permissions>\fR;
Sets the permissions of the log file, where \fI<permissions>\fR is a
standard POSIX.1 permissions value in octal format (see
.Xr chmod 1 ).  The default is 0644.
.It \fB user = \fI<user name>\fR;
Sets the owner of the log file.  Note that
.Xr mclogd 8
must be run as this user or root in order for this to have effect.
.It \fB group = \fI<group name>\fR;
Sets the group of the log file.  Note that
.Xr mclogd 8
must be run as a user who is a member of this group or root in order
for this to have effect.
.El
.Pp
An example files stanza is shown below.
.Pp
.Bd -literal
   files {
      logDirectory = "/usr/local/var/logs";
      logs {
          { filter="$mydaemons"; path="%H/%I"; user="dwm"; group="staff";
            perms=0644; period=1d; size=500k; keep=7; compress="bzip2"; },
          { filter="$myapps"; path="%H/myapps"; perms=0600; }
      };
   };
.Ed
.Sh FILTER EXPRESSIONS
Below is the pseudo-EBNF for the filter expression grammar.
.Pp
.Bd -literal
    expression: "(" expression ")"
      | "!" expression
      | expression "||" expression
      | expression "&&" expression
      | "facility" numerical_op facility_value
      | "severity" numerical_op severity_value
      | "host" equality_op quoted_string
      | "host" equality_op regular_expression
      | "ident" equality_op quoted_string
      | "ident" equality_op regular_expression
      | "pid" numerical_op unsigned_int
      | "msg" equality_op quoted_string
      | "msg" equality_op regular_expression;

    numerical_op: "<" | "<=" | ">" | ">=" | equality_op;
    equality_op: "=" | "!=";
    quoted_string: "'" [^']* "'";
    regular_expression: "/" [^/]* "/";
    unsigned_int: [0-9]{1,10};

    facility_value: kernel | user | mail | daemon | auth | syslog
      | lpr | news | uucp | cron | authpriv | ftp | local0 | local1
      | local2 | local3 | local4 | local5 | local6 | local7;

    severity_value: debug | info | notice | warning | err | crit
      | alert | emerg;
.Ed
.Sh FILTER EXPRESSION EXAMPLES
Select messages with a severity greater than debug from host foo.mcplex.net:
.Bd -literal
    (severity > debug) && (host = 'foo.mcplex.net')
.Ed
.Pp
Select messages with identifier \fImcroverd\fR or \fImctallyd\fR from hosts
outside of the mcplex.net domain:
.Bd -literal
    (ident = /(mcroverd|mctallyd)/) && (host != /.*\\.mcplex\\.net/)
.Ed
.Sh FILES
.Ss CONFIGURATION FILE
The standard location of the
.Xr mclogd 8
configuration file is \fI@prefix@/etc/mclogd.cfg\fR
.Pp
An example
.Xr mclogd 8
configuration is included in \fI@prefix@/etc/mclogd.cfg.example\fR
.Pp
.Sh SEE ALSO
.Xr mclogd 8 ,
.Xr mclog 1 ,
.Xr credence 1
